<font color="#FF0000">WHY IT HAPPENED</font><br>
<tt>Thu Nov 28 20:23:26 US/Eastern 1996
</tt><p>
For a few years after I returned I didn't really think about the war.  After a time I started to try to understand why I was involved and so many were not.  Then I decided that I needed to know what had happened.  I read many books and they only seemed to be the tiny tunnel vision that we all had of what we alone saw and understood.<br><br>
Finally I began to read such books as &quot;A Bright Shining Lie&quot; and others that were not about a personal experience so much as an understanding of what happened and why.  I think that this is what is missing from most discussions that I hear.  Most people just know what the TV debate is saying or what the political argument is that was last voiced.  We are basically ignorant about what happened.<br><br>
This fact will make it certain that the confusion over what to think about the war continues.  Also it makes it more likely that people who want to manipulate history for their own advantage now can do so.<br><br>
I sincerly hope that we can some how gain an unbiased education of what happened and why and come to terms with this great event in our life times.
